    "title": "Former Brevard Congressman Weldon nominated by Trump to head CDC",
    "text": "Trump nominates former Space Coast Congressman Weldon to head Centers for Disease Control\nPresident-elect Donald Trump has nominated Dr. Dave Weldon of Indialantic — a former Space Coast congressman — to become director of the [Centers for Disease Control and Prevention](https://www.cdc.gov/index.html).\nIn a statement released Friday night, Trump said Weldon \"understands American family values, and views health as one of utmost importance. Dave will prioritize transparency, competence and high standards at CDC. Dave will proudly restore the CDC to its true purpose, and will work to end the chronic disease epidemic, and make America healthy again.\"\nTrump's statement said: \"The current health of Americans is critical, and CDC will play a big role in helping to ensure Americans have the tools and resources they need to understand the underlying causes of disease, and the solutions to cure these diseases.\"\nWeldon, 71, served in Congress for seven two-year terms. He first won election in 1994 as part of the so-called \"Republican Revolution.\"\nDuring his tenure in Congress, Weldon championed religious and anti-abortion causes, gun rights and strengthening American national security. He also worked to support and expand the U.S. space program.\nWeldon helped secure money to construct the East Central Florida VA Clinic and to acquire land to expand the Archie Carr Wildlife Refuge in Brevard County.\nWhile serving in Congress, Weldon also supported multiple bills to criminalize human cloning.\nWeldon represented what was then Florida's 15th Congressional District, which included most of Brevard County, all of Indian River County, most of Osceola County and part of Polk County.\nDuring his time in Congress, Weldon sat on the Appropriations, Science, and Health and Human Services committees, among others.\nTrump's statement noted that, \"in addition to being a medical doctor for 40 years, and an Army veteran, Dave has been a respected conservative leader on fiscal and social issues, and served on the Labor/Health and Human Services Appropriations Subcommittee, working for accountability on HHS and CDC policy and budgeting. Dave also served in a leading role in Government Oversight and Reform Committee hearings, addressing issues within HHS and CDC. Dave has successfully worked with the CDC to enact a ban on patents for human embryos.\"\nTrump contended in his statement that \"Americans have lost trust in the CDC and in our federal health authorities, who have engaged in censorship, data manipulation and misinformation. Given the current chronic health crisis in our country, the CDC must step up and correct past errors to focus on the prevention of disease.\"\nLocated in Atlanta, the CDC is part of the [U.S. Department of Health and Human Services](https://www.hhs.gov/).\nA week ago, Trump nominated former independent presidential candidate Robert F. Kennedy Jr. to lead the Department of Health and Human Services.\nThe CDC is the nation's leading science-based, data-driven service organization that protects the public's health.\nIts current director is Dr. Mandy Cohen, an internal medicine physician who previously led the North Carolina Department of Health and Human Services.\nWeldon first came to Brevard in 1987, after serving six years as a physician in the U.S. Army. Weldon obtained his undergraduate degree in biochemistry from the State University of New York at Stony Brook and his medical degree from SUNY Buffalo School of Medicine. He is an internal medicine physician.\nWeldon ran for the U.S. Senate in 2012, but lost in a Republican primary to then-U.S. Rep. Connie Mack IV. Mack then lost to then-incumbent Democrat Bill Nelson in the general election that year.\nThis year, Weldon ran for a seat in the Florida House of Representatives, seeking the District 32 seat, which includes parts of central and south Brevard. But Weldon lost a Republican primary to then-Florida Sen. Debbie Mayfield, who subsequently defeated Democrat Juan Hinojosa in the Nov. 5 general election.\nWeldon was seeking to succeed incumbent Republican District 32 Florida Rep. Thad Altman, who was not able to run for reelection to the Florida House this year because of term limits. Altman this year won the District 5 seat on the Brevard County Commission.\nDave Berman is business editor at FLORIDA TODAY. Contact Berman at [dberman@floridatoday.com](mailto:dberman@floridatoday.com), on X at [@bydaveberman](https://twitter.com/ByDaveBerman) and on Facebook at [www.facebook.com/dave.berman.54](http://facebook.com/dave.berman.54)",
